<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870903-0029 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief:Supermarkets General Corp.</HL><DD> 09/03/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> SGLEARNINGS (ERN) </IN><TEXT>   Supermarkets General Corp., Woodbridge, N.J., reported fiscal second-quarter net income plunged 82% because of expenses incurred in its plan to go private.    The supermarket chain said it incurred pretax expense of $37 million in the quarter related to the planned leveraged buyout. This made net for the quarter ended Aug. 1 $3.5 million, or nine cents a share, compared with $19.9 million, or 52 cents a share, in the year-earlier period. Sales rose 5.7% to $1.47 billion from $1.39 billion.    First-half net fell 57% to $13.9 million, or 36 cents a share, from $32.2 million, or 86 cents a share. Sales rose 6.4% to $2.87 billion from $2.7 billion.    The leveraged-buyout expense included stock incentive, severance and early-retirement programs, plus legal and advisory fees, Supermarkets General said.    In New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday the company's stock closed down 50 cents a share, at $39.25. </TEXT></DOC>